<H3> <TI>   Reports on U.S. Air Base Issues in Okinawa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on U.S. Air Base Issues in Okinawa </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Task Force Welcomed </H4>

<F P=102> OW1706120794 Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO in Japanese 17 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 27 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1706120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yomitan -- The Japan-U.S. Joint Committee has 
established a task force to deal with the issue concerning the 
return of Yomitan Auxiliary Airfield. Yomitan village is 
welcoming this move. Deputy Mayor Keizo Yasuda said: "The 
official establishment of the task force will help promote the 
study of specific measures (for the airfield's return). This is 
a big step forward." 
  Meanwhile, the village is surprised that besides "the issue 
of looking for a substitute for the parachute training area in 
the airfield," "the possibility of removing Onna communications 
site" is also included in the items the task force is to 
discuss. The village has long thought that there was little 
possibility that the Onna communications site (also called the 
elephant's cage) would be removed. Thus, it has demanded the 
return of a part (0.6 hectare) of the airfield, not the whole of 
it, which covers 53 hectares. Taking into account the assertion 
that a radio wave buffer zone is indispensable for the 
communications site, the village has drawn up a returned land 
development plan that does not hinder the functions of the 
communications site. Thus, the village is perplexed at the fact 
that the task force will study the communications site's 
removal. Yasuda said: "We never expected the removal of the 
communications site would surface." 
  Nevertheless, the village is welcoming the establishment of 
the task force. Yasuda said: "It can be said that this is the 
result of our campaign calling for the airfield's return. We 
have conducted the campaign since Okinawa's reversion to Japan 
20 years ago. We expect and believe that a concrete result (a 
decision to return the airfield to the village) will be achieved 
in time for the 50th anniversary of the end of the Pacific war." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

