<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kansai Electric Testing New-Energy Home </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kansai Electric Testing New-Energy Home </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0331A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Jun 94 
p 13--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0331A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Kansai Electric Power has completed the 
next-generation energy residence, "The Horone," and, with solar 
batteries and storage batteries installed, has begun 
corroborative testing. It is an all-electric residence designed 
with a coffee shop on the first floor and so that a family of 
four can live on the second floor, and Kansai Electric Power 
will verify efficient use of energy incorporating solar 
batteries, an electric storage and heat storage system, and a 
reverse current system. The New Energy Development Organization 
(NEDO) has been commissioned for the corroborative tests and 
will continue them for a year jointly with the Electric Power 
Central Research Institute. The first floor of the building is 
scheduled to be affranchised as a coffee shop. 
  The output of the solar batteries will be a maximum of 4 
kilowatts. All the electric power used in the daytime cannot be 
supplied by solar batteries, but it serves to reduce the peak 
load. Electricity is stored in storage batteries using 
relatively cheap late night power, hot water heat and cold heat 
are stored in a heat storage tank, and used in air conditioning 
and heating during the day. 
  This equipment is controlled by an independent energy 
management system, which forecasts power load by anticipating 
the next day's weather and family activity schedule and 
automatically selects the most appropriate use of solar 
batteries and storage batteries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

