<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Admits Difficulties in Financing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Admits Difficulties in Financing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2106050494 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
2300 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2106050494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At a news conference on the national financial 
situation in the first six months of the year, Ministry of 
Finance representative revealed that the budget's revenue 
collection is so far progressing on schedule, but that the 
sources to subsidize the deficit are still limited. 
  Domestic savings are insignificant and foreign funds are not 
yet available. This limits spending to urgent and regular items 
and debt repayment only, while spending on capital construction 
has been low. By 10 April, the funds actually allocated for 
capital construction projects reached only 21.4 percent of the 
planned targets, with tardiness being the result of difficulties 
in with income sources. 
  Many projects are also suffering from a cessation of funds 
as 
they cannot meet fund allocation requirements. Of the 5,460 
investment projects this year, about three-quarters of them have 
not been able to fulfill requirements for capital allocation. 
Altogether, they represent six trillion dong in capitalization, 
and are mostly for projects initiated by the ministries of 
transportation, water conservancy, energy, culture and 
information, and banks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

