<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Il-song Gives On-the-Spot Guidance to Farm </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim Il-song Gives On-the-Spot Guidance to Farm </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2006231694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 2213 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2006231694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, June 21 (KCNA) -- The great leader 
President Kim Il-song gave on-the-spot guidance to the Kumdang 
Cooperative Farm in Onchon County, South Pyongan Province, on 
June 19. 
  He was accompanied by So Yun-sok, chief secretary of the 
South Pyongan Provincial Committee of the Workers' Party of 
Korea [WPK] and chairman of the South Pyongan Provincial 
People's Committee, So Kwan-hi, secretary of the WPK Central 
Committee, Kim Won-chin, chairman of the State Agricultural 
Commission, Kim Nak-hui, chairman of the South Pyongan 
Provincial Rural Economy Committee, and other officials 
concerned. 
  The cooperative farmers of Kumdang reaped a high yield of 
grain last year by strictly applying the chuche farming method 
of the WPK, and they have become able to look ahead to a rich 
harvest this year through vigorous efforts to increase the grain 
output. 
  President Kim Il-song got first-hand knowledge of crop 
conditions, going round the fields of the farm and noted with 
deep satisfaction that the agricultural working people of the 
Kumdang Cooperative Farm had created good crop conditions by 
concentrating every effort on farming in hearty response to the 
party's agriculture-first policy. To do a successful farming 
is most important in resolving the problems of food, clothing 
and housing, he said, adding that the agricultural working 
people must do all farm work on a scientific and technical basis 
as required by the chuche method of farming, deeply conscious 
that they are responsible for the rice granaries of the nation. 
He said various kinds of fertilizers must be applied to crops 
in a rational ratio in order to increase the grain output. 
  He praised the Kumdang Cooperative Farm for effectively 
irrigating nonpaddy fields with the introduction of various 
economic and rational methods of irrigation. All the 
cooperative farms must mobilize all the irrigation facilities to 
supply enough water to maize and other crops, he added. 
  He said that in order to increase agricultural production, 
the leading officials of agriculture must enhance their role and 
the industrial sector must supply larger quantities of farming 
materials to the countryside. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

