<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Failure of Cambodian Talks Discussed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Failure of Cambodian Talks Discussed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1806110894 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 18 Jun 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BK1806110894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Thailand yesterday suggested the Cambodian 
government and the Khmer Rouge try to agree on the agenda before 
starting peace negotiations to ensure progress. 
  "It is better than talking about the issues which each side 
cannot accept. 
  "Otherwise, there would be no breakthrough," Foreign 
Minister 
Prasong Sunsiri said when asked to comment on the failure of the 
round-table discussions in Phnom Penh on Thursday. 
  The second round of talks, which resumed on Wednesday 
following the one hosted by King Norodom Sihanouk in Pyongyang 
last month, was a deadlock as both sides could not agree on the 
agendas. 
  Sqn Ldr [Squadron Leader] Prasong reiterated that the peace 
negotiation could not be successfully concluded in just one 
meeting and encouraged the Cambodian leaders and the Khmer Rouge 
representatives to find opportunities for more talks. 

</TEXT>

