<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, U.S. Eye Tourism To Cut Trade Deficit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo, U.S. Eye Tourism To Cut Trade Deficit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006144294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1429 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
will set up a forum to promote tourism between the two countries 
as one way to help correct the bilateral trade imbalance, the 
Ministry of Transport said Monday [20 June]. 
  The program aims to double the total number of tourists to 
each country every year to about eight million people by the 
year 2000. 
  Officials said the ministry has agreed with the U.S. 
Commerce 
Department to set up the joint forum for the program and to hold 
the first meeting in the U.S. sometime in fall. 
  Some 3.5 million Japanese visit the U.S. every year at 
present, while 500,000 Americans come to Japan annually. 
  Japanese tourists pump about 10 billion dollars more into 
the 
U.S. economy per year than is generated in tourism-related 
spending in Japan by Americans. 
  If the number of tourists on each side was doubled and thus 
Japanese tourism spending in the U.S. double-folded, it would 
help put a dent in the huge trade imbalance which is currently 
in Japan's favor, the officials said. 
  The program is also expected to deepen people's 
understanding 
of one another's nation, they said. 

</TEXT>

