<H3> <TI>   Further Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata's Remark Clarified </H4>

<F P=102> OW2106053594 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 0300 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2106053594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report; from the "NHK News" program] </F>
  [Text] At today's meeting of the House of Councillors' 
Budget Committee, Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata explained his 
recent remark during a public speech on the street that he 
believed North Korea did not possess nuclear weapons. He said 
that was more an expression of his hope. 
  At the House of Councillors' Budget Committee today, Minao 
Hattori of the Liberal Democratic Party and others questioned 
Hata's remark during a wayside speech on 18 June that he 
believed North Korea did not actually possess nuclear arms and 
had no intention to produce them. They said this is in conflict 
with the government's official view so far. 
  In reply, Hata explained that since North Korea claims that 
it has neither the capability, nor the intention to manufacture 
nuclear arms, his remark was really an expression of his hope. 
He also said he regretted that his statement could lead to 
misunderstanding. He indicated the government's consensus on 
this matter is that North Korea may have produced more plutonium 
than it has declared, and it would be a serious matter if such 
plutonium is being used to manufacture nuclear weapons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29740 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas119_a_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-119 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reports on Issues Related to DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Conditional Economic Aid Offered </H4>

<F P=102> OW2106142794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1421 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2106142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 21 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa on Tuesday reiterated a demand that Pyongyang provide 
information that would enable international monitors to verify 
whether North Korea had extracted plutonium from its nuclear 
facilities in the past. 
  Japan "would be able to extend a helping hand to North Korea 
if the history of the operations of its nuclear facilities were 
revealed to verify whether plutonium is clandestinely 
stockpiled," Kakizawa told a house of representative panel on 
cabinet affairs. 
  The foreign minister also expressed readiness to give 
economic aid, including funds to finance construction of 
light-water nuclear reactors, if Pyongyang is forthcoming in 
divulging data on the history of its nuclear reactors. 
  He also reiterated Japan's resolve to seek the deletion of 
an 
"enemy clause" from the U.N. Charter in the process of ongoing 
discussions on reforming the framework of the U.N. Security 
Council. 
  The charter has described Japan, Germany and other states 
defeated by the Allied Forces during World War II as enemy 
states -- a description that has embarrassed these U.N. member 
states, now seeking to contribute to global peace. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

