<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Small Manufacturers Prefer China as Investment Site </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Small Manufacturers Prefer China as Investment Site </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006143894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1407 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006143894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- More than half of small 
Japanese manufacturers responding to a poll on their planned 
overseas investments see China as their first choice, a Tokyo 
Chamber of Commerce and Industry survey showed Monday [20 June]. 
  The survey covered 2,300 small and midsize manufacturing 
members of the chamber. Of the total, 22.1 percent, or 509 
firms, responded. 
  According to results of the survey and observations of 
industry analysts, Japan can expect further "hollowing out" of 
its industrial base in the coming years. The analysts noted 
that high domestic wages, coupled with an eroding international 
competitive power due to the yen's rise, are prompting smaller 
firms to set up shop in foreign countries. 
  Of the respondents, 24.2 percent said they have already set 
up wholly owned subsidiaries abroad or acquired an equity stake 
in overseas businesses. 
  The survey also found that 21.6 percent of the respondents 
plan to invest abroad. Of these, 91.8 percent said they intend 
to invest in Asian countries, with China ranking the highest in 
popularity, followed by Indonesia, Malaysia and Thailand. 

</TEXT>

