<H3> <TI>   SDPJ To Urge Hata To Voluntarily Resign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ To Urge Hata To Voluntarily Resign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006134794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1337 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2006134794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 20 KYODO -- The leadership of the 
Social Democratic Party (SDP) [Social Democratic Party of Japan 
-- SDPJ] decided Monday [20 June] night to seek a summit meeting 
with Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata as early as Wednesday to 
request his voluntary resignation, SDP officials said. 
  They said SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama and senior SDP 
officials also decided to draw up a blueprint of a new 
government, of which the nation's second-largest political party 
would be part. 
  Earlier in the day, Murayama said his party will seek a 
temporary alliance with the largest opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) to call for a snap poll if planned 
realliance talks with the ruling coalition fail. 
  Murayama told a meeting of the party's former Diet members 
that the SDP should join hands with the LDP to create a 
temporary cabinet if talks with the minority coalition of Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata break down and, consequently, Hata is 
forced to resign after a no- confidence vote. 
  The LDP, ousted last year after 38 years in power, has 
pledged to submit a no-confidence motion against the shaky Hata 
cabinet after the budget bills pass the Diet, expected within a 
week. 
  If the SDP supports the LDP move, that will clinch the no- 
confidence vote, leaving Hata with a choice of resigning with 
his ministers or dissolving the House of Representatives for 
snap elections. 
  Hata has made clear that he will step down if a 
no-confidence 
vote passes the lower house. 

</TEXT>

