<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ's Blueprint for New Coalition Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ's Blueprint for New Coalition Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2106075694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0647 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2106075694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 21 KYODO -- The leadership of the 
Social Democratic Party (SDP) [Social Democratic Party of Japan 
-- SDPJ] on Tuesday drew up a blueprint of a new coalition 
government on the premise that the coalition government of Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata resign voluntarily. 
  The blueprint said a new government, in which the SDP hopes 
to take part, should have a basic philosophy of democracy, 
freedom, fairness and peace based on respect for the 
Constitution. 
  A third coalition government must establish trustworthy 
relations among the coalition parties, it said, indirectly 
criticizing the formation in late April of a parliamentary group 
by other coalition partners excluding the SDP. 
  The SDP withdrew from the coalition following the formation, 
forcing Hata to form the first minority government in 39 years. 
  Basic policies of a new coalition government should be 
agreement among parties on the coalition governments of Morihiro 
Hosokawa and Tsutomu Hata, it said. 
  As for tax system reform, the blueprint calls for abolition 
of the consumption tax and agrees to raise indirect tax to cope 
with the aging of society. It wants to enact bills for tax 
system reform by the end of the year. 
  The SDP urges the peaceful settlement of the North Korean 
nuclear issue by cooperating with the United States, South 
korea, China and Russia. 
  The plan also proposed setting up a council of Diet leaders 
and holding regular summit meetings of the parties to ensure 
transparency of decision-making procedures. 
  The SDP has said it will return to the ruling coalition if 
Hata and his cabinet ministers resign en masse voluntarily. 
  SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama said Monday his party will 
move to form a caretaker government with the largest opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) to oversee a general election if 
talks with the coalition fail. 
  The LDP plans to submit a no-confidence motion against the 
Hata cabinet after passage of the state budget for fiscal 1994, 
expected Thursday. If a no-confidence vote is approved, Hata 
must either dissolve the House of Representatives for a snap 
general election or disband his cabinet en masse. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

