<H3> <TI>   Press Reports Indicate Economic Recovery </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Press Reports Indicate Economic Recovery </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    BOJ's Monthly Report </H4>

<F P=102> OW2106104894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1022 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2106104894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 21 KYODO -- Japan's economy has stopped 
weakening and is headed for recovery on the back of gradual 
recovery in personal consumption, the Bank of Japan (BOJ) said 
Tuesday [21 June] in a monthly report on monetary and economic 
trends. 
  Among factors behind the central bank's views were strong 
investment in the housing and public sectors, bottoming out of 
industrial production and steady progress in inventory 
adjustment, as well as recovering personal consumption, the 
report said. 
  The report, however, noted corporate capital spending 
continues to decline in the manufacturing sector as a whole, 
while that in the nonmanufacturing sector remains stagnant. 
  In the labor market, growth in the number of employees 
continues to slow due to limited recruitment of new graduates, 
though the ratio of job offers to job applicants has stopped 
decreasing, the report said. 
  As to the nation's gross domestic product (GDP) data for the 
January-March quarter, just released by the Economic Planning 
Agency, Kagehide Kaku, research and statistics director at the 
central bank, told reporters the figures are within expectations 
and in line with the bank's judgments. 
  Asked about the possible impact of the yen's recent 
strengthening against the dollar on a burgeoning economic 
recovery, Kaku only said, "we are paying significant attention" 
to the yen's appreciation. 
  In this regard, Kaku reiterated the bank's view that the 
economy seems to have taken one step forward toward recovery, 
but ups and downs are expected amid remaining risks such as the 
yen's resurgence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

