<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Reports Indicate Economic Recovery </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Press Reports Indicate Economic Recovery </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    GDP, GNP Growing Steadily </H4>

<F P=102> OW2106080394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0705 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2106080394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 21 KYODO -- Japan's economy grew a real 
1.0 percent in the first quarter this year from the last three 
months of 1993, or at an annual rate of 3.9 percent, the 
Economic Planning Agency said in a preliminary report Tuesday. 
  Domestic demand accounted for 0.8 percent of the inflation- 
adjusted growth of the gross domestic product (GDP), while 
external demand contributed 0.2 percent. 
  Consumer spending gained 1.4 percent in the first three 
months of this year, while corporate plant and equipment 
investment declined 1.0 percent. 
  The real gross national product (GNP) in the same quarter 
expanded by 0.8 percent from the preceding three months, or an 
annualized 3.3 percent. 
  GDP and GNP are the total output of goods and services, with 
GDP excluding net income from overseas. 
  Meanwhile, Japan's GDP in fiscal 1993 that ended March 31 
remained unchanged from the previous year in real terms, while 
the real GNP decreased 0.1 percent. 
  Of the 1.0 percent growth for the first quarter, domestic 
demand accounted for 0.8 percent, while external demand 
contributed 0.2 percent. 
  The GDP sank 0.7 percent in the fourth quarter of 1993. 
  Consumption further gained 1.4 percent, compared with a 0.7 
percent rise in the previous quarter, while plant and equipment 
spending declined 1.0 percent but improved from a negative 3.8 
percent in the October-December period. 
  Active government spending in line with pump-priming 
packages 
helped consolidate the upward move, the EPA [Economic Planning 
Agency] said. 
  The real gross national product (GNP) in the first quarter 
rose an annualized 3.3 percent. Of the data representing the 
total output of goods and services, GDP excludes income from 
overseas. 
  For fiscal 1993, figures released simultaneously showed that 
the GDP growth remained flat, or only fractionally on the plus 
side of 0.03 percent. 
  The 0.0 percent performance was the weakest since the 
negative performance of 0.03 percent posted in fiscal 1974. 
  On a GNP basis, the fiscal 1993 economy shrank 0.1 percent. 
  Returning to the GDP, the government said that as a result 
of 
the fiscal 1993 showing, the current fiscal year will 
technicallly see a 0.4 percent growth even if all the quarters 
post zero expansion. 
  It said, however, an average 0.77 percent, or an annualized 
3.12 percent, growth is necessary in each quarter in the current 
fiscal year to accomplish the official forecast of a 2.4 percent 
expansion. 
  Private economists agree with optimistic remarks by the 
EPA's 
Tanaka, saying it looks like Japan is beginning to prepare for a 
major recovery. 
  "I think the fiscal year-end factor and a reaction to the 
contraction in the fourth quarter of 1993 combined to boost the 
figure for the January-March quarter," said Atsushi Miyawaki, a 
senior economist at Japan Research Institute. 
  "But generally speaking, Japan appears on the verge of an 
upward swing," he added. 
  Bank of Tokyo analyst Yozo Nishimura said conditions have 
considerably improved and that a substantial revival can be 
expected in fiscal 1995 after a gradual recovery in the current 
fiscal year. 
  But Miyawaki said there is still a possibility of negative 
growth in the April-June period in reaction to the healthy 
first-quarter performance. 
  Personal income remains sluggish, he noted, and the major 
focus will be whether the effects of the summer income tax cuts 
will persist in the following months. 
  Nishimura was a bit more optimistic and expected flat growth 
as the worst case for the April-June period. 
  "The risk factor is the effect of the appreciation of the 
yen 
against the dollar, which could throw cold water on buoyant 
export activities," he said. 
  Economists estimate Japanese exporters have their 
boom-or-bust rate set at 105 yen to the dollar. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

