<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-119 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Pushing for Mid-July N-S Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Pushing for Mid-July N-S Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2106052094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0513 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2106052094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 21 (YONHAP) -- The government is pushing 
to hold the proposed inter-Korean summit by mid-July after 
completing preliminary contacts between the two sides' deputy 
premiers by early next month. 
  Responding to the offer of an unconditional summit made by 
North Korean leader Kim Il-song, a government official said 
Tuesday that the two sides will meet beforehand to schedule the 
summit for July in Seoul or Pyongyang, or a third place named by 
North Korea. He added, however, that contacts with Pyongyang 
will follow Seoul's judgement that North Korea is sincere about 
the summit. 
  The summit's success or failure is totally up to the North 
Koreans despite varying internal and international conditions, 
he stressed, forecasting the meeting would be held in July if 
North Korea showed sincerity. 
  Meanwhile, the government plans to accept any change of date 
for the preliminary contacts if North Korea counterproposes a 
date that is within one week of June 28, the date proposed by 
Prime Minister Yi Yong-tok. 
  If North Korea launches another political offensive, such as 
the 10-point program adopted by its Supreme People's Council on 
April 7 last year, the government will stop seeking a summit and 
instead intensify its efforts to secure a UN resolution imposing 
sanctions on the North. 
  Earlier Tuesday, Deputy Premier and National Unification 
Minister Yi Hong-ku met with senior presidential secretary for 
foreign and national security affairs Chong Jong-uk to discuss 
preparations for the preliminary contacts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

