<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Christopher: Carter Statement Not U.S. Position </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Christopher: Carter Statement Not U.S. Position </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1806020494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0155 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1806020494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 17 (YONHAP) -- U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher, referring to former President Jimmy 
Carter's reported statement that Washington has suspended its 
bid to apply sanctions against North Korea, said Friday "it is 
different" from Washington's official position. 
  A high-ranking official at the South Korean Embassy in 
Washington disclosed that Christopher conveyed the U.S. 
Government's position to the South Korean Government through 
Assistant Secretary of State Winston Lord. 
  Christopher said the United States would continue 
consultations on sanctions against Pyongyang at the U.N. 
Security Council until it became apparent that North Korea had 
frozen its nuclear development program. 
  Meanwhile, South Korean Ambassador to Washington Han Sung-su 
met with Assistant Secretary of State Robert Gallucci to 
exchange views on American policy toward North Korea, which 
seems muddled after Carter's recent statement in Pyongyang. 
  At the meeting, Gallucci was quoted by the high-ranking 
official as stressing that "Carter's statement in Pyongyang is 
not the official position of America." 

</TEXT>

