<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Experts on Japan's Import Efforts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Experts on Japan's Import Efforts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2106040294 Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Jun 94 
Evening Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2106040294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chaired by Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, the 
government held a trade meeting to talk about how Japan, which 
runs a huge trade surplus, should buckle down to the task of 
expanding imports. The meeting was held at the prime minister's 
official residence on the morning of 15 June. 
  Following the cabinet's 29 March approval of an outline 
foreign economic reform plan, Vice Chairman of Caterpillar Inc. 
Wagsland [as published] and other foreign experts gave their 
views on government efforts to ease regulations and improve 
other matters. In response, Prime Minister Hata explained his 
resolve to expand Japan's imports. 
  He said: "It will be painful. But, we will not be able to 
enjoy an affluent life unless we realize these economic reforms, 
including the promotion of deregulation and the improvement of 
market access." 
  At the meeting, Vice Chairman Wagsland gave his assessment 
of 
Japanese efforts in such areas as deregulation and improved 
market access. 
  He said: "Some people in the American financial world are 
skeptical about the seriousness of efforts by Japanese society 
as a whole." 
  Chairman of the Berlin Chamber of Commerce and Industry 
Kramp 
[as published) criticized Japan's bureaucratic system. 
  He said: "Although there are no clear import barriers, 
practical regulations such as administrative guidance still 
exist." 
  Chairman of the Thai Trade Council Wanli [as published] 
called for Japanese contributions to economic development in 
Asia. 
  He said: "We hope Japan will hand over to us industrial 
sectors which have lost their competitive power." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

