<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Talks With U.S. Around 5 Jul Considered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Talks With U.S. Around 5 Jul Considered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2106135394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1347 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2106135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 21 KYODO -- Japan is considering 
holding ministerial-level trade talks with the United States in 
Washington around July 5, a senior official of the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry said Tuesday. 
  The talks are aimed at striking an accord on the three 
priority areas for the "framework" negotiations before the July 
8-10 Naples summit of the Group of Seven (G-7) key industrial 
countries, the official said. 
  Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa and International Trade and 
Industry Minister Eijiro Hata will likely visit the U.S. before 
flying to Italy for the annual summit, said the official who 
declined to be named. 
  The three framework trade priority sectors are insurance, 
government procurement, and trade in autos and auto parts. 
  The official said the two countries will hold 
subcabinet-level talks on auto and auto parts trade in 
Washington in the first half of next week, aiming to reach 
consensus on "objective criteria" as a yardstick to assess the 
openness of the Japanese auto market. 
  The official said he is not certain about whether Tokyo and 
Washington will reach a complete agreement on auto trade before 
the Naples summit. 
  Japan will decide whether or not to postpone final 
settlements on auto trade beyond the summit at the end of next 
week by evaluating results of discussions at the planned 
subcabinet-level talks, the official said. 
  He said subcabinet-level talks will also be held in 
Washington next week on government procurement and insurance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

