<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kakizawa, Kantor Plan To Meet in U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakizawa, Kantor Plan To Meet in U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2106022294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0207 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2106022294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 21 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa said Tuesday he plans to visit the United States this 
weekend for bilateral trade "framework" talks with U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor. 
  Kakizawa said he revealed his plan for the U.S. visit to 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata in a meeting after the regular 
cabinet session and Hata approved it. 
  But his U.S. visit depends on what happens in the Diet, 
Kakizawa told reporters. 
  Japan and U.S. officials have said they hope to reach an 
agreement in the talks on setting up a new bilateral trade 
framework before the Naples summit of the Group of Seven (G-7) 
industrialized nations in July. 
  Hata and U.S. President Bill Clinton are scheduled to meet 
in 
Naples. 
  Kakizawa is tentatively scheduled to leave for the U.S. on 
Friday [24 June] evening and return to Tokyo on Monday. 
  The two sides are considering a West Coast city such as Los 
Angeles or San Francisco as the venue of the Kakizawa-Kantor 
meeting, government sources said. 
  Kantor has strongly requested a meeting with Kakizawa, the 
sources said. 
  Japan and the U.S. have also considered a meeting between 
Kakizawa and U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, but 
gave up on that as it was too difficult to arrange, they said. 

</TEXT>

