<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Seek DPRK Nuclear Program Disclosure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo To Seek DPRK Nuclear Program Disclosure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2106210694 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2106210694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government will ask the United States and South 
Korea to take concerted steps with Japan to bring North Korea's 
past developments in the nuclear field to light, a government 
source disclosed on 20 June. The government has decided to do 
so in response to the prospect of the resumption of high-level 
U.S.-DPRK talks and the DPRK's proposal to hold North-South 
summit talks. The government intends to speedily set 
itineraries for Prime Minister Hata to visit South Korea and 
Foreign Minister Kakizawa to visit the United States. They will 
seek to shape a consensus with the United States and South Korea 
in dealing with the issue of the past developments in North 
Korea's nuclear program. 
  With regard to the DPRK nuclear issue, the United States has 
set as a condition of the resumption of the stalled U.S.-North 
Korean high-level talks the DPRK's acceptance of special 
inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to 
determine whether Pyongyang has in the past diverted plutonium 
to build nuclear weapons. During his meeting with former U.S. 
President Carter, North Korean President Kim Il-song said that 
as conditions for resuming the stalled U.S.-North Korean 
high-level talks, the DPRK will allow IAEA inspectors to remain 
at the North's nuclear facilities and that North Korea will 
return completely to the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT). 
  In response, Assistant Secretary of State Robert Gallucci 
indicated that the U.S. Government would accept the proposal put 
forward by the DPRK president for resuming the high-level talks, 
saying, "If North Korea is found to have promised to freeze 
major elements of its nuclear program when we pursue another 
round of high-level talks between the United States and North 
Korea, this would be a constructive step." In this way, the 
United States has softened its preconditions for resuming the 
stalled U.S.-DPRK high-level talks. 
  The IAEA has said that following North Korea's complete 
removal of fuel rods at an experimental nuclear reactor, it is 
be unable to verify developments in the DPRK's nuclear program. 
The same government source said, "The U.S. Government intends 
to leave the issue of verifying past developments of North 
Korea's nuclear program to the North-South summit talks, in 
anticipation of the impossibility of verifying them." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29941 </DOCNO>
