<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Automakers Cooperate on Engine Parts in Thailand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Automakers Cooperate on Engine Parts in Thailand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0312A Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Jun 94 
Evening Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0312A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] The three companies of Toyota Motor, Nissan Motor, 
and Isuzu Motors have agreed in principle to supply each other 
with diesel engine parts in Thailand. They are filling in the 
details and soon will sign an agreement. The Thai Government has 
set forth an auto policy to boost the domestic production rate 
for diesel engine parts to 70 percent (currently 50 percent) by 
June 1996. Because each of the three companies has local 
production bases, they will divide labor in production of engine 
parts, effectively using each others' facilities and aiming to 
achieve the domestic production rate within a short period while 
pursuing merit of scale. 
  The target will be diesel engine parts for one-ton pickup 
trucks (including for export) that they each produce locally in 
Thailand. 
  Toyota has built a casting plant for engine manufacture in 
the outskirts of Bangkok with "Siam Toyota Manufacturing," a 
joint venture with Siam Cement Group, a large Thai conglomerate, 
as the nucleus, and soon will put it in operation. The local 
sales companies of Nissan and Isuzu have also inaugurated 
"Naharoha Industries," a joint investment with Siam Naharoha 
Foundry, a casting parts company of the Siam Cement Group, and 
have a casting factory in the outskirts of Bangkok. 
  Siam Toyota will supply block castings to Nissan and Isuzu, 
and Naharoha Industries is studying in the direction of 
supplying Toyota with head parts and crankshafts. 
  The Thai Investment Committee (BOI) is obligated to boost 
the 
domestic rate for diesel engine parts from the current 50 
percent to 60 percent by fiscal 1994 (July 1994 to June 1995), 
and to 70 percent during fiscal 1995 (July 1995 to June 1996). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

