<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Tells US EAEC Not To Weaken APEC </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Tells US EAEC Not To Weaken APEC </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2306084794 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0600 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2306084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Malaysia appreciates the U.S. concern over the 
formation of the East Asia Economic Caucus, EAEC, but assures 
the United States that the proposed forum will not weaken or 
undermine APEC [Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation). Defense 
Minister Datuk Sri Najib Tun Razak said it was rather 
disheartening to learn that the United States had formally 
informed Japan that it was opposed to the ASEAN proposal of the 
EAEC. 
  He said it was rather surprising since the concept ideally 
promotes market-driven open regionalism and supports regional 
economic cooperation. He said this when opening the two-day 
fifth U.S.-Malaysia colloquium jointly organized by ISIS 
[Institute of Strategic and International Studies] Malaysia and 
the Asia Foundation in Washington. Datuk Sri Najib, in his 
opening remarks, said that he was aware of the domestic public 
opinion in the U.S. and even Congressional opposition to such an 
initiative, especially when it does not include the U.S. 
  U.S. Assistant Secretary for East Asian and Pacific Affairs 
Winston Lord, who was present at the gathering, said that the 
U.S. had given its initial response on the EAEC proposal to its 
ASEAN friends as well as Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-29969 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas121_h_94002" </HT>


