<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Country Said Now Third Largest Coal Exporter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Country Said Now Third Largest Coal Exporter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2206110494 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 1500 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2206110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Indonesian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ambyo Mangunwijaya, president director of the 
state-run Bukit Asam Coal Mining Company, said Indonesia, with 
coal export figures of 20 million tons in 1993, has become the 
world's third largest coal exporter. 
  He said that the constant boosting of production would also 
increase Indonesia's coal exports, which may reach 40 million 
tons by the end of the current Sixth Five-year Development Plan 
(Pelita VI) in 1999. 
  According to Ambyo Mangunwijaya, by the conclusion of Pelita 
VI, Indonesia's coal output is projected to increase to 71 
million tons per year, of which 31 million tons are for domestic 
consumption and 40 million tons for export. 
  To boost production, the Bukit Asam Coal Mining Company has 
entered into cooperation with a number of mining contractors, 
both local and foreign. 

</TEXT>

