<DOCNO> FBIS4-29991 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas121_j_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister: Rice Situation, No Imports Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister: Rice Situation, No Imports Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2206140794 Jakarta ANTARA in English 1200 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2206140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta ANTARA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jakarta, June 22 (ANTARA) -- The government has 
appealed to the farmers not to hold back their rice stocks 
because the government is constantly in need of rice in 
substantial quantities to maintain stability, State Minister 
Ibrahim Hasan told the press here on Wednesday. 
  The state minister for food affairs /chairman of the 
national 
logistics agency made these remarks after giving an account of 
the development of the national food stock to President Suharto 
at the Merdeka [Presidential] Palace. 
  Minister Ibrahim Hasan said that the food stock controlled 
by 
the government reached at present 700,000 to 900,000 tonnes, but 
it will continue to increase until it reached the safe level of 
1.2 to 1.3 million tonnes. 
  The government will continue to purchase rice not only to 
meet the people's demand but also to prevent a negative impact 
of the dry season, he added. 
  The Central Bureau of Statistics has predicted that the dry 
season this year will cause a reduction of 2.7 per cent in the 
production of rice. 
  Indonesia's demand for rice each year reaches about 2.5 
million tonnes. 
  The minister said that although rice production declined, 
the 
government had no intention whatsoever to import this commodity. 
  Although Indonesia will not commercially import rice, but it 
will receive 500,000 to 600,000 tonnes of rice in the next few 
months as reimbursements of the rice lent by Indonesia to 
several countries, including the Philippines. 
  The minister also reported about the result of the recent 
meeting of 16 ministers in the fields of agriculture and food in 
Montevideo, Uruguay, discussing the implementation of the 
Uruguay Round which was ratified in Morocco recently. 
  One of the items discussed at the meeting was the 
abolishment 
of subsidies on agricultural produce which have so far been 
provided by advanced as well as developing countries. 
  Commenting on the result of the meeting, the head of state 
said that Indonesia should constantly implement the Uruguay 
Round decisions, however with taking the national interest into 
consideration. 
  "We should always give priority to the national production 
and imports only as complementary", Minister Ibrahim Hasan said, 
quoting the president. 
  He also stressed that Indonesia would fulfilled its 
obligation to import 70,000 tonnes of rice, although it would 
only be implemented early in 1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

